For anyone curious, here&#x27;s a comparison (that I wrote a couple days ago) of FizzBuzz in K vs. q vs. python... please note the insane syntax for K4 (which is a proprietary language of KX Systems and is thus undocumented).<p>K<p><pre><code>    \c 150 100 
    c:{$[0=x-5*x div 5;$[0=x-3*x div 3;&quot;CracklePop&quot;;&quot;Pop&quot;];$[0=x-3*x div 3;&quot;Crackle&quot;;x]]}&#x27;1_!101 
    r:{x@&~x in &quot;\&quot;&quot;} 
    p:{-1 r .Q.s x}
    p c 
    \\
</code></pre>
q (the &quot;readable&quot; wrapper around K4&quot;)<p><pre><code>    \c 150 100
    c:{$[0=x mod 5;$[0=x mod 3;&quot;CracklePop&quot;;&quot;Pop&quot;];$[0=x mod 3;&quot;Crackle&quot;;x]]} each 1_til 101 -1 ssr[.Q.s c;&quot;\&quot;&quot;;&quot;&quot;] 
    \\
</code></pre>
Here’s a python (2.7) version of the program written in as unreadable as I could muster<p><pre><code>    for i in map(lambda x: &quot;CracklePop&quot; if not x % 3 and not x % 5 else &quot;Crackle&quot; if not x % 3 else &quot;Pop&quot; if not x % 5 else x, xrange(1,101)): print i
</code></pre>
Here it is in normal python (2.7)<p><pre><code>    for x in xrange(1,101):
        if not x % 5: 
            if not x % 3: 
                print &quot;CracklePop&quot; 
            else: 
                print &quot;Pop&quot; 
        elif not x % 3: 
            print &quot;Crackle&quot; 
        else: 
            print x</code></pre>
